From a12b0228cea47eb5f9b8d6b7c77d00e27430c18b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Peter Jung <admin@ptr1337.dev>
Date: Mon, 11 May 2026 19:00:01 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 30/32] drm/i915/psr: exit Panel Replay during updates to work
 around ALPM lag

Panel Replay ALPM AUX-Less wake/sleep cycling cannot resume selective
updates at frame rate on the LGD OLED panel in the Dell XPS 14
DA14260. The panel's internal timing engine appears to need a
per-frame timing beacon to resume quickly after ALPM sleep; without
it, the source commits at 120 Hz but visible frames land around
15 Hz.

Work around by temporarily exiting Panel Replay in
frontbuffer_flush() before each frame update. Re-entry into PR (with
ALPM) is deferred by 50 ms via dc3co_work so that during continuous
motion the link stays on (cursor/video smooth), and PR re-engages
after 50 ms of no further updates (idle power savings preserved).

The delay was chosen empirically:

  | Delay  | Idle (10x avg) | Cursor motion (3x avg) |
  |--------|----------------|------------------------|
  |  50 ms |     3268 mW    |        8749 mW         |
  | 100 ms |     3436 mW    |        9088 mW         |
  | 200 ms |     3484 mW    |        9104 mW         |
  | stock  |     3384 mW    |  ~15 Hz visible lag    |
  | PSR2   |     4060 mW    |        9191 mW         |

50 ms gives the best idle and cursor-motion power while remaining
subjectively identical in smoothness to longer delays.

Repurpose the existing dc3co_work delayed_work as the re-entry timer:
each frontbuffer_flush cancels+rearms it to 50 ms, and the work
handler calls intel_psr_activate() when it fires.

Signed-off-by: Gaggery Tsai <gaggery.tsai@intel.com>
Signed-off-by: Peter Jung <admin@ptr1337.dev>
